{
    "ocr_text": "Prince George Hotel, Toronto, Ont. Canada
XXXXXXXXXXXXXX November 9, 1909
Mr. Oscar B. Hawes,
5224 Greene St.
Germantown, Pa.
Dear Sir:
Your favor of November 4th is received and contents noted. In reply I beg to say that if you can so arrange it, I will
be glad to accept your invitation to deliver an address before the
Mens Club of Germantown, but at present I cannot give you any definite promise.
I am now in this city attending the 29th Annual
Convention of the American Federation of Labor, and would suggest
that you write me again, upon this subject, to our Washington address, sometime in the month of December when I may be able to
give you a more definite reply.
Very truly yours,
President
American Federation of Labor.",
    "summary": "The president of the American Federation of Labor acknowledges the receipt of Mr. Oscar B. Hawes' letter dated November 4th. He expresses an interest in accepting an invitation to deliver an address to the Men's Club of Germantown but cannot make any definitive promises at the moment. The president is currently attending the 29th Annual Convention of the American Federation of Labor in Toronto and suggests that further communication on this matter should be directed to their Washington address in December for a more definitive reply.",
    "date": "1909-11-09",
    "is_printed": true,
    "is_legible": true
}
